<div class="dnd_post-card__lower-section">
<h2 class="dnd_post-card_title">
<a href="https://granta.com/introduction-deutschland/">
Introduction
</a>
</h2>
<h4 class="dnd_post-card_author">
<a class="contributor-link" href="https://granta.com/contributor/thomas-meaney/">Thomas Meaney</a>
</h4>
<p class="dnd_post-card_text">
This issue of <em>Granta</em> collects writing headed full tilt in the opposite direction from the literary lassitude of the land.<br/><br/>The editor introduces the issue.
</p>
</div>
</div> </div>
<div class="dnd_column_dd_span4">
<div class="dnd_post-card">
<div class="dnd_post-card__upper-section">
<h6 class="dnd_post-card__category-text">
<a href="https://granta.com/explore?cat=fiction"><span class="dnd_post-card__red-text">Fiction </span></a>
<span class="dnd_post-card__divider">|</span>
<a href="https://granta.com/products/granta-166"><span>Issue 166</span></a>
<span class="dnd_post-card__padlock"></span>
</h6>
<a href="https://granta.com/repetition/">
<div data-bg="https://granta.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Vidgis-Hjorth.jpg" class="dnd_post-card_img background-align__middle rocket-lazyload" data-background="https://granta.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Vidgis-Hjorth.jpg" style></div>
</a>
</div>
<div class="dnd_post-card__lower-section">
<h2 class="dnd_post-card_title">
<a href="https://granta.com/repetition/">
Repetition
</a>
</h2>
<h4 class="dnd_post-card_author">
<a class="contributor-link" href="https://granta.com/?post_type=contributor&p=115794">Vigdis Hjorth</a>
</h4>
<p class="dnd_post-card_text">
The people she longed to be understood by, the ones at whom her anxious hope was pinned, were her parents. <br/> <br/> Fiction by Vigdis Hjorth, translated by Charlotte Barslund.
</p>
</div>
</div> </div>
<div class="dnd_column_dd_span4">
<div class="dnd_post-card">
<div class="dnd_post-card__upper-section">
<h6 class="dnd_post-card__category-text">
<a href="https://granta.com/explore?cat=essays-and-memoir"><span class="dnd_post-card__red-text">Essays &amp; Memoir </span></a>
<span class="dnd_post-card__divider">|</span>
<a href="https://granta.com/products/granta-166"><span>Issue 166</span></a>
<span class="dnd_post-card__padlock"></span>
</h6>
<a href="https://granta.com/ecce-senex-stephen-james-joyce/">
<div data-bg="https://granta.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/James-Scudamore.jpg" class="dnd_post-card_img background-align__middle rocket-lazyload" data-background="https://granta.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/James-Scudamore.jpg" style></div>
</a>
</div>
<div class="dnd_post-card__lower-section">
<h2 class="dnd_post-card_title">
<a href="https://granta.com/ecce-senex-stephen-james-joyce/">
Ecce Senex: Stephen James Joyce
</a>
</h2>
<h4 class="dnd_post-card_author">
<a class="contributor-link" href="https://granta.com/?post_type=contributor&p=115803">James Scudamore</a>
</h4>
<p class="dnd_post-card_text">
He was a Joyce, not a Joycean, yet considered himself the supreme arbiter of what constituted valuable Joyce scholarship. At the same time, he admitted that he rarely read anything in full. <br/> <br/> James Scudamore on trying to ghostwrite Stephen James Joyce's memoir.
</p>
</div>
</div> </div>
</div>
</div>
